cs.NI, cs.LG, cs.SY, cs.IT, cs.AI 

This paper is about wireless access networks and their ability to support diversified quality of service (QoS) metrics required by various types of Internet-of-Things (IoT) devices. The proposed framework is based on distributed policy learning, which involves the use of neural networks to approximate the function mappings from inner-states to transmission probabilities. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture), cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.SY (Systems and Control), cs.IT (Information Theory), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). Among these, cs.NI is the most likely category since the paper is primarily concerned with wireless access networks and their ability to support QoS requirements. The use of neural networks also suggests that the paper could belong to cs.LG and cs.AI. The focus on distributed policy learning and the iterative approach used to improve the function mappings suggest that the paper could also belong to cs.SY and cs.IT.
